x4freetext: Van de Graaff driven neutron source
Neutrons from 1 to 4 MeV.
TiT solid target.
Monoenergetic neutron beam.
Two sets of photovoltaic cells in a compact
geometry placed at 5 mm on both sides of the Am-243
targets. Each photovoltaic cell of rectangular shape
20x40 mm  consists of a monocristalline silicon
structure covered with a comb-like conducting grid
-for fission fragments detection.
The photovoltaic cells have no sensitivity to neutron
beam and an intrinsic efficiency of 95(+-1)%. Fission
detectors were placed in front of each Am target in a
very compact geometry to obtain geometrical efficiency
of about 70%.
A polypropylene (PP) foil ((C3H6)n) placed
at 45 mm from the 243Am targets and 80 mm from neutron
source. This foil placed at 0 degree with respect to
the incident-neutron beam served as a radiator to
convert quasi-monoenergetic neutrons into protons.
Recoiling protons emitted from the neutron-proton
elastic scattering reaction occurring in the PP foil,
were detected at 74.4 +- 0.2 mm downstream, by silicon
telescope consisting of an energy-loss detector of
55 microm positioned in front of a residual-energy
detector of 700 microm. Several thicknesses (10 to
50 microm) of the PP foil were used to keep the energy
loss of the recoiling protons below 15% for all
incident neutron energies.
The ensemble PP-telescope formed neutron flux detector.
Protons recoiling from neutron scattering in
the PP foil were detected by means of DE-E telescope
located at 75 mm from the foil.
Stack target irradiation
At zero degree as flux monitor

x4codes.shortRef: Jour: Nuclear Data Tables (Nuclear Data Sect.A), Vol.9, p.137 (1971)

x4freetext: Back-to-back deposits of two 243Am targets placed at
39 mm from the neutron source and at 0 degree with
respect to the incident neutron beam.
Targets were prepared at the Lawrence Berkeley National
Laboratory by electroplating onto a 0.6-mm-thick
stainless steel backing with a deposit diameter of 6mm;
the sample thicknesses were 546(+-2) microg/cm2 and
564 (+-2) microg/cm2.
The isotopic purity of the Am
targets was 99.96 (+-0.01)%.
The target characteristics were measured by alpha
spectrometry - revealed the presence of a very small
quantity of 249Cf.
For backgrounds.
In principle, the neutron flux on the PP foil is
obtained by integrating the spectrum of recoil protons
combined with the n-p elastic cross section and the
telescope efficiency using Monte Carlo simulations of
neutrons and protons passing through the experimental
setup, which takes into account the resolution of the
charged particle beam, the energy loss of the charged
particle beam in the deuterium or tritium targets, the
angular distributions of the neutron beam,the angular
distribution of the (n,p) elastic scattering cross
sections, the proton energy loss in the PP foil, the
energy resolution of the Si telescope. Then the neutron
spectrum, the mean value of (n,p) elastic scattering
cross section, the proton detector efficiency as
function of neutron energy were deduced. (n,p) elastic
scattering anisotropy was taken into account in the
calculations of the proton detection efficiencies.
Kinematic effects and the uncertainties on geometrical
parameters were taken into account to define precisely
the value and the uncertainty of fission efficiency.
Precision better than 0.5% over a
wide range of neutron energies (1 meV to 20 MeV).
Total standard deviation,
without solid-angle correlation - LAMBDA1=LAMBDA2=0.
Statistical standard deviation.
